pr_title: feat(merge): Add filter for intermediate reports
pr_body:
I have added a filter for intermediate reports which will filter out reports from the merge output.
Do users want to filter out the reports on the basis of a date range as well?  If that is the case, should I add `-s --start-date` and `-e --end-date` arguments. Or should I  just convert `-F --filter` to a dictionary type input.?

[{'comment_id': 654050951, 'comment_body': 'We should be saying "open source" with a space rather than a dash.  (I know, I've seen grammar checkers say otherwise, but convention is definitely in favour of the space over the dash.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 17, 23, 40, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 654051383, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
properly configured, installation will result in `cve-bin-tool` being accessible
```
We don't need the word "the" here because we're using "installation" as a verb.  e.g. "If your shoes are properly tied, running will be safer"', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 17, 23, 41, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 654052725, 'comment_body': 'Convention for "command-line" versus "command line" is a bit more mixed and you see both used in practice, but I'm going to rule no dash here either due to the fact that we use "command line" with a space everywhere else.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 17, 23, 46, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 654054823, 'comment_body': "This section reminded me: do we have the json schema for this written somewhere explicitly so we can use it for json validation?  If you don't have it yet, please file a bug to do that later.  You can take a look at the code in `test/test_json.py` for how to do the validation. We'll want that run by default if it doesn't provide a huge performance hit (and as an option if it does).", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 17, 23, 52, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 654055706, 'comment_body': "Let's put a link here to the how-to guide you made so that people know they can click through to get more information.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 17, 23, 55, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: feat: Add NVD CVE Retrieval API
pr_body:
Need updating the logs while loading the *.gzip.json files
Note - It takes a lot of time
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 669182567, 'comment_body': 'I think we need a little bit more documentation here.  
1. Why would one want to use this API?  
2. What are the performance impacts (some example numbers/percentages would be good)
3. Does this use less bandwidth?
4. Are there any other implications users should know about?

Assume the user isn't going to read the paper (although it's definitely good to link) and is just going to decide "should I use this flag?" based on what's in the doc.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 13, 23, 47, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674214843, 'comment_body': 'You import `DISK_LOCATION_DEFAULT` from `nvd_api` but it is being redefined on line 50:
```python
DISK_LOCATION_DEFAULT = os.path.join(os.path.expanduser("~"), ".cache", "cve-bin-tool")
```
They are the same.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 18, 5, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674220289, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
            self.LOGGER.info("[Using NVD API]")
```
There are no placeholders, it's just a regular string', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 18, 14, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674223127, 'comment_body': '`session` is not accessed, did you mean to use it on line 115?
```py
session=None,
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 18, 18, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674225554, 'comment_body': '`FileIO, GzipFile, run_coroutine` are never used', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 18, 22, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674260854, 'comment_body': "Hm, I don't think this works correctly. For +3 timezone it returns `UTC-03:00` and for -4 timezone it returns `UTC--4:00`.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 18, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674261366, 'comment_body': 'this `index` variable is being incremented in the loop but never used', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 18, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674264025, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
        all_cve_data["CVE_data_numberOfCVEs"] = str(len(all_cve_data["CVE_Items"]))
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 23, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674264223, 'comment_body': '`year_wise_data` is never accessed, did you want to use it at line 258?
```py
self.year_wise_data = await self.filter_year_wise_data(self.year_wise_data)
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 23, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674279250, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
def filter_by_id(cve, update_data):
    """Function to filter out duplicate CVE entries in case of incremental update"""
    id = cve["cve"]["CVE_data_meta"]["ID"]
    return all(
        id != update_cve["cve"]["CVE_data_meta"]["ID"] for update_cve in update_data
    )
```
This reads easier imo.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 48, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674283699, 'comment_body': 'We are limiting session in cvedb by using limits_per_host=19
Initially I thought about using the same session in nvd_api.py
But there is no such restriction in the SOAP API.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 53, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'imsahil007', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674286976, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
      -n, --nvd             use NVD's CVE and CPE APIs (as opposed to NVD's JSON Vulnerability Feeds)
```

Looking at https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/data-feeds, they officially call the two types "CVE and CPE APIs" versus "JSON Vulnerability Feeds" so let's make our terminology match theirs.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 19, 57, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674291392, 'comment_body': "```suggestion
      -n, --nvd  {api, json}           choose method for getting CVE lists from NVD
```

Actually, why don't we just go ahead and make it so that `--nvd=api` and `--nvd=json` are both explicit options with `json` as the default for now.  Then, assuming we don't have any issues and the performance seems good, we could plan to make `--nvd=api` be the default in some future release as @anthonyharrison suggests.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 20, 1, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674336951, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
```
Unused now', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 20, 51, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 674343347, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
    """Function to filter out duplicate CVE entries in case of incremental update"""
```
There are 5 doc strings in this file that start with 4 double quotes instead of 3.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 21, 21, 2, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677794890, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
The CVE API is the next stage in providing up to date vulnerability information for NVD data consumers. The results from this API are updated as quickly as NVD website (unlike the traditional feeds which have explicit update interval of once per day).
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 27, 20, 57, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677795229, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
To use the NVD API, simply use `-n api` or `--nvd api`:
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 27, 20, 57, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677795551, 'comment_body': '```suggestion
 With the help of this REST API, we can fetch just the newly added/modified NVD data using the timestamp of your current local database copy.
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 27, 20, 58, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 677863076, 'comment_body': "I wonder if we should do a tiny refactor here so we're not storing it again in the class, but I can't decide if that actually makes any sort of meaningful difference other than making it easier to search on a single variable name.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 27, 23, 16, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: fix(nvd_api): refactor nvd_api-cvedb and remove json cache
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 682896389, 'comment_body': 'I have subtracted 2 minutes offset from (cvedb.db) timestamp considering the case NVD updates their database just when we populate the database. We can always update any repeated record in cvedb without any issue.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 19, 23, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'imsahil007', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682907725, 'comment_body': 'Just a style nit but class names should normally use the CapWords convention (same for `TestNVD_API`).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 19, 42, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 683312702, 'comment_body': 'Thanks @Molkree 
I will keep that in mind.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 5, 10, 1, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'imsahil007', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 683317162, 'comment_body': 'According to this [style guide](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#descriptive-naming-styles), it is better to use all caps while using acronyms. As `HTTPServerError` is better than `HttpServerError`.
We are using the same convention for CVEScanner and CVEDB.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 5, 10, 8, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'imsahil007', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 683373136, 'comment_body': "> We are using the same convention for CVEScanner and CVEDB.

`CVEScanner` and `CVEDB` follow this convention, yes ðŸ˜ƒ 
But `NVD_API` is not because it has an underscore. It's actually pretty similar to `CVEDB` (vs `CVE_DB`).

[Class Names](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#class-names)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 5, 11, 38, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Molkree', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 685457431, 'comment_body': "I'm willing to accept NVD_API for readability reasons here, regardless of conventions.  Honestly, I'd be willing to rework CVEDB to be CVE_DB for the same reason, but I suspect that veers well into waste-of-time territory.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 9, 19, 19, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'terriko', 'type': 'User'}]
